******
[3] USA: 2nd nurse infected with Ebola, may have felt ill earlier
Date: Thu 16 Oct 2014
Source: Huffington Post [edited]
http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/10/16/amber-vinson-ill-friday-ebola-symptoms_n_6000062.html


2nd nurse infected with Ebola may have felt ill as early as Friday
------------------------------------------------------------------
[The 2nd nurse] to be infected with Ebola after caring for patient Thomas Eric Duncan, may actually have had symptoms as early as last Friday [10 Oct 2014], health officials said. The nurse at Texas Health Presbyterian Hospital Dallas, where Duncan was being treated and later died, flew to Cleveland [Ohio] on Friday to help plan her wedding. She returned to Dallas on Monday [13 Oct 2014]. She called health officials before her flight on Monday, reporting a minor fever. But the Center for Disease Control and Prevention told her it was okay to get on the plane. Because she may have been sick earlier than officials believed, the CDC is expanding their investigation to people the 29-year-old nurse may have come into contact with over the weekend. Included are passengers who were on her flight to Cleveland, Fox 8 Cleveland reported.

Frontier has reached out to passengers on 5 flights that used the same airplane [the nurse] flew on, the Denver Post reported. Anyone who flew with her is encouraged to call 1-800-CDC-INFO. A CDC spokesperson told the Wall Street Journal on Thursday [16 Oct 2014] that it was possible that passengers on [the nurse's] Friday [10 Oct 2014] flight may have contracted the virus. Earlier this week, CDC Director Tom Frieden said that because her fever was low on Monday, it is unlikely that she was contagious. Still, he said it was mistake for her to fly.

7 people have placed themselves under self-quarantine in Northeast Ohio after coming into contact with [the nurse] during her trip to Ohio. According to Fox News 8, people who were at the Coming Attractions bridal shop in Akron [Ohio] on 11 Oct 2014 from 12 to 3:30 p.m. have been asked to call the health department. Some schools in Texas and Ohio have also canceled classes because students or staff flew on the same airplane as [the nurse].

[Byline: Amanda L. Chan]

